.TH ConsoleDisplay 3 "2025-11-12" "ConsoleDisplay 1.0.0" "C++ Library Manual"
.SH NAME
ConsoleDisplay \- 512x512 console grid for pixels and text

.SH SYNOPSIS
.nf
#include <ConsoleDisplay/library.h>

namespace console_display {
  class ConsoleDisplay {
  public:
    static constexpr int WIDTH = 512;
    static constexpr int HEIGHT = 512;

    enum class CellType : std::uint8_t { Empty, Pixel, Text };

    struct Cell {
      CellType type;
      bool     pixelOn;
      char     ch;
    };

    ConsoleDisplay();
    void clear();
    void setPixel(int x, int y, bool on = true);
    void setText(int x, int y, char ch);
    void setTextString(int x, int y, const std::string& s);
    void fillPixels(bool on);
    Cell getCell(int x, int y) const;
    std::string toString(char pixelChar = '#', char emptyChar = ' ') const;
    void render(std::ostream& os) const;
  };
}
.fi

.SH DESCRIPTION
ConsoleDisplay provides a simple 512x512 character grid that can be rendered
to the console or converted to a string. Each cell may act either as a pixel
(on/off) or as a text character. This is useful for prototyping ASCII/console
visualizations and for unit tests that compare expected string output.

.SH CONSTANTS
.TP
.B WIDTH, HEIGHT
Both are 512. Valid coordinates are 0 <= x < WIDTH and 0 <= y < HEIGHT.

.SH TYPES
.TP
.B enum class CellType { Empty, Pixel, Text }
Cell role: unused, pixel, or text.
.TP
.B struct Cell
Holds the cell's current state: type, pixel flag, and character.

.SH METHODS
.TP
.B ConsoleDisplay()
Constructs a new display and clears all cells to Empty.
.TP
.B void clear()
Resets all cells to Empty with a space character.
.TP
.B void setPixel(int x, int y, bool on = true)
Marks the cell as a Pixel; sets it on/off. Out-of-bounds coordinates are ignored.
When on, the cell renders as the chosen pixel character (default '#'); otherwise as the empty character (default space).
.TP
.B void setText(int x, int y, char ch)
Marks the cell as Text and stores the character. Out-of-bounds are ignored.
.TP
.B void setTextString(int x, int y, const std::string& s)
Writes a string horizontally starting at (x, y). Stops at the right edge. If x < 0, the visible portion is clipped. If y is out of bounds, the call is ignored.
.TP
.B void fillPixels(bool on)
Sets every cell to Pixel with the given on/off state.
.TP
.B Cell getCell(int x, int y) const
Returns a copy of the cell at (x, y). If out of bounds, returns an Empty cell.
.TP
.B std::string toString(char pixelChar = '#', char emptyChar = ' ') const
Converts the entire grid into a string of HEIGHT lines, each WIDTH characters long, separated by newlines. Pixel cells render as \fBpixelChar\fR if on, otherwise \fBemptyChar\fR. Text cells render as their stored character.
.TP
.B void render(std::ostream& os) const
Streams the output of \fBtoString()\fR using default characters.

.SH EXAMPLES
.nf
#include <iostream>
#include <ConsoleDisplay/library.h>

int main() {
  console_display::ConsoleDisplay disp;
  disp.setPixel(10, 10, true);
  disp.setTextString(0, 0, "Hello");
  disp.render(std::cout);
}
.fi

.SH NOTES
All operations silently ignore out-of-bounds coordinates for convenience.

